----
-name: Node TypeScript ESM imports in this project
-description: How `node --test` strip-only mode handles TypeScript imports and what syntax it rejects.
----
-
-This project runs TypeScript tests directly with `node --test` (Node's built-in TypeScript loader in strip-only mode). It is **not** a full `tsc` compilation step.
-
-**Rule:** Relative imports must include the `.ts` extension, even when the target is a TypeScript file.
-
-- `import "./foo"` fails with `ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND` or `ERR_UNSUPPORTED_DIR_IMPORT`.
-- `import "./foo.ts"` resolves correctly.
-- Directory imports (e.g., `import * as schema from "./schema"`) are not supported; use `import * as schema from "./schema/index.ts"` instead.
-
-**Rule:** Avoid TypeScript-only class syntax that strip-only mode cannot erase.
-
-- Parameter properties in constructors are rejected: `constructor(public readonly x: string) {}` throws `ERR_UNSUPPORTED_TYPESCRIPT_SYNTAX`.
-- Use an explicit property declaration and assignment inside the constructor instead.
-
-**Why this matters:** The production build uses esbuild, which hides these issues. Service tests that import `@workspace/db` or other workspace packages directly under `node --test` will hit the strict ESM resolution rules. We had to add `.ts` extensions to all relative imports in `lib/db/src/schema/*.ts` and `lib/db/src/helpers/index.ts` so the DB package could be loaded by the Node TypeScript loader.
-
-**How to apply:**
-
-- When writing new service tests or any file that may run under `node --test`, always use `.ts` extensions for relative imports and for dynamic imports (`await import("./index.ts")`).
-- Do not rely on esbuild's loose resolution in test-only code.
-- Keep constructors compatible with strip-only mode if the class lives in code loaded by the test runner.
\ No newline at end of file
